post_text:
Band Camp 2020 is almost here! I look forward to making music with you!

Schedule
Freshmen Camp - Friday, Aug. 7, 7am-11am
Drumline/Colorguard Camp - Saturday, Aug. 8, 8am-4pm
Student Leadership meeting - Sunday, Aug. 9, 2pm
Full Camp - Monday-Wednesday, Aug. 10-12, 7am-3pm

Things students need at camp:
>Sun screen, sunglasses, hat
>Water jug - water fountains are OFF except for the touchless refill.
>Athletic wear (including shoes)
>Instrument (your own or school)
>3 ring binder, page protectors for music
>Face mask
>A great attitude!

We will adhere to social distancing recommendations as best we can. Face masks will not be required outdoors when distancing is maintained. Face masks will be required indoors when not actively playing a wind instrument.

This year's camp will certainly be different, but as we Greenbacks do, we'll make the best of it! I look forward to making music with all of you again for the first time in a long time!!

post_text:
Hey everyone! This upcoming Sunday at 3pm would have been the band's final concert of the year, and obviously that won't be happening. My heart breaks that we won't be performing what was to be a great slate of music. One of the other important things we do at that concert is honor the band's achievements through the year, our lettering students, our band's awards, and honor our graduating seniors. I'm especially sad that we can't do those things. Band is about the people in it, and it is what we do both as individuals and as a group that make it special.

To that end, Sunday at 3pm I will go live from the band room to do my best to brag on the students' achievements, our lettering students, Seniors, and the like.

Perhaps now more than ever is a good time to think about instrument sanitation. To that end, I have prepared a document to help guide you through the process. While this can be done at home, the best possible job will be by instrument repair professionals. I can refer you to several professional shops for that.

Also, I know not everyone took their instruments home for spring break. At this time, we are not allowing instruments in the school to be retrieved. Once a plan to allow safe transfer is in place, I will post another update here.

post_text:
Upcoming competitions update!

On Monday the 21st the band will be performing at the FHSU Marching Festival. Our performance time is 11:15am. The awards are at about 3:30, after which we will come home.

On Wednesday, October 30th the band will perform at the Andover marching festival. Performance time is slated for 10:42am.

For both events, we will leave the school at 8:00am. Students should arrive by 7:15 to get everything ready for travel. They will need to bring lunch money for both events, they will have concessions available.

I believe we are primed for an excellent performance at Fort Hays, and we'll use the feedback from that event to be better yet for Andover!

post_text: I'm so incredibly proud of all the POSCKS Band members! We knew camp would be a day short this year, yet everyone worked their tails off and we put the whole first song of the show on the field, music and all! Going into camp, I wondered if it was possible. Yet the kids stepped up, worked hard, and made it happen! What a testament to solid work ethic and ability to work with others towards a common goal! While we're not the quality we will be, this is a great achievement for only 3 days work! Congrats on a great camp to the students, thank you Parents for the snack donations, and to Mr. Wade and Mrs. Malone for contributing your talents! I know this will be another great year for the band!

Great first day for the POSCKS band camp! Our freshmen worked hard this morning and the afternoon meeting was faster and smoother than I was hoping for. The vibe in the room was great and I'm positive this is going to be another great year!
Tomorrow is Color Guard and Drumline at 8am for their minicamp. Mon-Wed. is full camp at 7am. Those on time (aka early) on Monday get doughnuts, my treat!
Thank you to those parents who have donated snacks to help keep the kids energized! After tallying up today, we could still use a bit more. There is enough for Monday and Tuesday, I don't think there is quite enough for Wednesday. Granola bars, snack crackers, or fruit snacks would be the items of need if you can help a little.
Go Greenbacks!

post_text:
Parents! I'm still looking for more snack donations to help keep the kids energized and healthy for band camp next week. Things we could use include...
>Individual chip bags
>Granola bars
>Chex mix (individually bagged)
>Fruit snacks
>Etc.
I believe I have enough Gatorade mix to get through each day. Being able to provide the kids with snacks helps keep them energized and healthy. Camp is a lot of work and they appreciate it! If you can help out, please comment below or message me through this page, or send me an email. Kids should have on hand a water bottle and sun screen. Thanks for all you do to support the kids!

If you can help out, please comment below or message me through this page, or send me an email. Kids should have on hand a water bottle and sun screen. Thanks for all you do to support the kids!

post_text:
Two of our band and choir students are giving a piano recital in preparation for a bigger competition coming up. Please see the information below from Duane Hanks, their piano teacher and the PHS choir accompanist...

Our next Pratt Musical Expressions concert will be this Sunday, April 14, at 2 p.m. at All Saints Episcopal Church. Please note the change in time to 2 p.m.

This will be our first ever piano-only concert. I will be playing along with Kahrie Stegman and Grace May. The three of us are traveling to Dallas in May to be adjudicated, and in my case this will be the final step to earn a diploma in piano performance. I will say more about it on Sunday, but playing our music for an audience is an important part of the preparation for going to Dallas.

We have a variety of music from Handel to contemporary, and the program includes Beethoven's Moonlight Sonata.

Hope to see you there!

post_text:
I am incredibly proud of the Greenback Band today! We have kept up our tradition of excellence, bringing home a Superior rating at State Large Group. These kids have dealt with some adversity to earn this honor, 12 kids were gone all week on an (amazing!) NYC trip and only got back at 1:30am today! We haven't had a full rehearsal in who knows how long, too. Yet these individuals came together to make great music as one ensemble. Great job, and you've earned an easy Friday, after we finish clean-up :)
Also, shoutout to Brandon Wade for leading the choirs to an excellent day, and my student helpers for making today run smooth as we hosted the festival.
Onwards and upwards!
üíöüê∏üéµ

We have several events happening over the next couple weeks! We're a little over a week from heading to Florida, and then we have our annual Mass Band concert after we get back. See below for the details!

Sunday 3/10 - 3pm - Student meeting and luggage drop-off for Florida. We will review expectations and the schedule one more time. Parents are welcome to attend this. This is mandatory for all students going to Florida unless you talk to me ahead of time to make other arrangements. Your luggage and instrument should be ready to go at this time.

Monday 3/11 - 5am - Arrive at band room for those going to Florida. Bring your carry on items. Bus carry-on is limited to a backpack, throw blanket, and pillow. We roll out at 6am.

Saturday 3/16 - 11:59pm - Arrival back at PHS from Florida. This time will likely change due to travel, I will update as needed.

Thursday 3/21 - 7:30pm - Mass Band concert for 6-12 grade. Students need to be ready in the PHS gym at 6:45pm for rehearsal. Doors open to the audience at 7:15.

Call time for the HS band tonight is 5:45. 7th/8th band students should arrive at the game in time for the 7pm kickoff. At the end of the 1st quarter, MS band students should meet in the band room. Following halftime, they are free to go. Dress warm, preferably in Pratt colors if you can.

An extra thank you goes out to our admin for making this possible, the parents who have helped along the way, and especially Brandon Wade and Arica Malone for your skills!

post_text:
Parents and community! I want to inform you of a SUPER EASY way to passively support the band! Its as easy as shopping at Dillons like you normally would while using your Plus card after enrolling in their Community Rewards program.
On the Dillons website, find the "Savings and Rewards" menu, and then "Dillons Community Rewards." There will then be a link to enroll in the program. It will ask for a code, ours is "UK411" and should come back as Pratt USD 382 -- Band.
Simply enroll and shop as your normally would, and a small portion of your spending will go directly to the band to help us pay for trips, equipment, and new music.
As always, thank you for supporting the Pride of South Central Kansas and Go Greenbacks!
text:
Parents and community! I want to inform you of a SUPER EASY way to passively support the band! Its as easy as shopping at Dillons like you normally would while using your Plus card after enrolling in their Community Rewards program.
On the Dillons website, find the "Savings and Rewards" menu, and then "Dillons Community Rewards." There will then be a link to enroll in the program. It will ask for a code, ours is "UK411" and should come back as Pratt USD 382 -- Band.
Simply enroll and shop as your normally would, and a small portion of your spending will go directly to the band to help us pay for trips, equipment, and new music.
As always, thank you for supporting the Pride of South Central Kansas and Go Greenbacks!

post_text:
Band parents and community!
I'm looking to try something new this year during band camp. Since the kids are working incredibly hard both inside and outside, I'd like some help keeping them fueled and hydrated during camp. What I'd like to do is have a snack and perhaps some gatorade available to everyone during a morning session break and perhaps once in the afternoon too. Enrollment is right around 60 members. What I'm asking for is donations of...
>powdered gatorade (we have drink coolers)
>paper cups
>chex mix
>chips
>crackers
>cookies
>etc.
>Prepackaged snack-sized preferred.
A couple helpers to distribute would be appreciated as well. I myself got enough popsicles that each band member will have at least one each day of camp. If you can help, comment below or send me a message. Thanks so much for supporting the kids and their hard work!!

Also, I'd like to thank Beth Shelden for putting this all together!

post_text:
On Tuesday, October 11, the PHS band traveled to Winfield for the Mound of Sound Marching Festival at Southwestern College (Winfield) and had a very successful day. This festival is unique because bands are grouped into four classes based on size and bands receive placings inside those classes (Pratt was Class 2 with bands such as Winfield).

Pratt was judged the best overall Class 2 band.

We also received best in class in every single judged category: Music, Visual, General Effect, Percussion, Guard, and Drum Major (Stephanie Reichenberger), receiving a higher score in each of those categories than any other Class 2 band.

The band received an overall score of a 2 (on a scale of 1-5), missing a 1 rating by .55 points (we received a 74.45 and a 75 is considered a 1 rating).

This is only the third year for this festival and the first time that Pratt has received best in class. The band improved their score from last year by 18%, by far the greatest increase of any band in attendance.

Unfortunately the weather didn't cooperate tonight and the football game was canceled. The Pride was ready to bring it and had some fun playing inside while waiting. This piece, Twist-n-Wiggle, is one we would have played. (Excuse the poor recording/sound quality).

The game has been rescheduled for Saturday at 4:00. However, due to nearly every student also being involved at the same time with cross country, tennis, and the PHS musical, we will not be able to have a band at the game. We will be at the next home game ready to have a great time!

post_text:
On Saturday, April 9, the band program took about 80% of the band to KSHSAA Regional Solo/Small Ensemble Music Festival in Dodge City. This is by far the largest group we have taken in several years. The students received the following ratings (scale of 1-5 with 1 being the highest):

Clarinet Ensemble--1 (advanced to state)
Saxophone Quart--1 (advanced to state)
Soloist Katie Buhler--1 (advanced to state)

Bass Clarinet Trio, Trumpet Trio, Trombone Quartet, Brass Ensemble, Percussion Quartet--2
Soloists Alesha Bergner, Dalton Davidson, Samantha Harrison Esmeralda Lopez, David Schotte--2

Katie Buhler, the Clarinet Ensemble, and the Saxophone Quartet will all perform at the state festival in Andover on Saturday, April 23.

Today the concert band performed at the CKL League Festival and received an overall score of a 1 (Superior). This is the highest rating the band can receive!

Additionally, most students performed in one of seven different chamber groups (3-9 members), giving them an opportunity to perform in a more personalized setting. The picture is of one of the small groups performing and features six freshman and a junior.
